<p>Companies publishing 16+ blog posts monthly generate 4.5x more leads than those publishing fewer. Volume matters. But only when every piece targets a specific keyword with clear intent.</p>
<h2>Technical SEO for B2B Websites</h2>
<p>B2B websites face specific technical challenges. Enterprise sites often have complex architectures, gated content, and JavaScript-heavy pages.</p>
<h3>Site Architecture</h3>
<p>Organize your site by solution, not by internal department. Buyers do not care about your org chart. They care about their problem.</p>
<p><strong>Good structure:</strong></p>
<pre><code>/solutions/[problem-area]/
/resources/[content-type]/
/customers/[case-studies]/
/pricing/
</code></pre>
<p><strong>Bad structure:</strong></p>
<pre><code>/about-us/departments/marketing/resources/
/library/assets/2024/q3/whitepaper-v2/
</code></pre>
<p>Clean URL structures help Google understand your site hierarchy. They also help users find what they need. For more on URL best practices, read our <a href="/blog/url-structure-seo/">URL structure guide</a>.</p>
<h3>Page Speed and Core Web Vitals</h3>
<p>B2B sites frequently underperform on Core Web Vitals. Heavy images, unoptimized JavaScript, and third-party tracking scripts slow page loads.</p>
<p><strong>Priority fixes:</strong>
- Compress images to WebP format
- Defer non-critical JavaScript
- Reduce third-party scripts (chat widgets, analytics, marketing tools)
- Implement lazy loading for below-the-fold content
- Use a CDN for global delivery</p>
<p>Sites that pass Core Web Vitals see 24% fewer page abandonment. For B2B, every lost visitor is a potential $50K+ deal walking away.</p>
<h3>Crawlability and Indexation</h3>
<p>Common B2B crawl issues:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Gated content:</strong> Google cannot read content behind login walls. Provide ungated summaries or teaser content.</li>
<li><strong>JavaScript rendering:</strong> Heavy SPA frameworks (React, Angular) cause indexation problems. Use server-side rendering or pre-rendering.</li>
<li><strong>Faceted navigation:</strong> Product pages with filters create duplicate content. Use canonical tags and <code>noindex</code> on filtered pages.</li>
<li><strong>Thin resource pages:</strong> PDF-only pages with no HTML content rank poorly. Add summary text to every resource page.</li>
</ul>
<p>Run a <a href="/blog/technical-seo-checklist/">technical SEO audit</a> quarterly to catch these issues before they impact rankings.</p>
<h3>Schema Markup for B2B</h3>
<p>B2B sites benefit from specific schema types:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Organization schema</strong>. Company name, logo, contact information, social profiles</li>
<li><strong>Article schema</strong>. For blog posts and resource content</li>
<li><strong>FAQ schema</strong>. For product pages and support content</li>
<li><strong>HowTo schema</strong>. For implementation guides and tutorials</li>
<li><strong>SoftwareApplication schema</strong>. For SaaS product pages</li>
</ul>
<p>Pages with schema markup achieve 20-40% higher click-through rates in search results. For B2B, where every click represents a potential enterprise deal, that CTR improvement translates directly to pipeline. Learn more in our <a href="/blog/schema-markup-seo-guide/">schema markup guide</a>.</p>
