<h2>B2B Link Building That Works</h2>
<p>Link building drives authority. Authority drives rankings. But B2B link building operates differently than consumer SEO.</p>
<h3>Tactics That Work for B2B</h3>
<p><strong>1. Original research and data reports.</strong>
Publish proprietary data. Survey your customers. Analyze your product usage data. Original research earns backlinks passively as journalists and bloggers cite your findings.</p>
<p><strong>2. Industry expert contributions.</strong>
Contribute guest articles to industry publications. Not SEO blogs. Your industry publications. An accounting SaaS company should publish in accounting journals, not marketing blogs.</p>
<p><strong>3. Tool and resource creation.</strong>
Build free tools (calculators, templates, assessments) that your target audience needs. A free <a href="/tools/seo-roi-calculator/">SEO ROI calculator</a> earns backlinks from every blog post that discusses SEO budgeting.</p>
<p><strong>4. Partnership and co-marketing content.</strong>
Co-create content with complementary B2B companies. Joint webinars, co-authored reports, and shared research studies double your link acquisition from a single effort.</p>
<p><strong>5. HARO and journalist requests.</strong>
Respond to journalist queries with expert commentary. B2B executives have unique expertise that journalists need for articles about business trends, technology, and industry developments.</p>
<p><strong>6. Customer success stories as linkable assets.</strong>
Turn your best case studies into standalone data stories. "How [Client] Reduced Customer Acquisition Cost by 63% in 9 Months" is more linkable than a generic case study PDF. Include specific numbers, timelines, and methodology that other sites want to reference.</p>
<p><strong>7. Industry conference and event content.</strong>
Recap key takeaways from industry conferences. Interview speakers. Publish data shared at events. Conference content earns links because attendees share it and non-attendees reference it as the next best thing to being there.</p>
<h3>What Does NOT Work for B2B</h3>
<ul>
<li>Mass guest posting on irrelevant blogs</li>
<li>Paid link placements in directories</li>
<li>Comment spam or forum link drops</li>
<li>Reciprocal link exchanges</li>
<li>Press release link farming</li>
</ul>
<p>The common thread: manipulative tactics fail in B2B because B2B buyers and Google both evaluate trustworthiness carefully. One backlink from a respected industry publication outperforms 100 links from generic blogs.</p>
<p>For a complete strategy, read our <a href="/blog/link-building-strategies/">link building guide</a>.</p>
